International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: 20 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Xinhuanet, 7 Jul 2004 [machine translated, edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/world/2004-07/07/content_1580035.htm>

Mongolia has diagnosed 10 anthrax infections
-----------------------------------------------
The Mongolian Disease Control and Disaster Prevention Bureau reported to
the media, on 7 Jul 2004, that 7 people in the province had reported having
fever, and, that an additional 3 persons had been diagnosed with anthrax.
According to the person in charge, during the period from the end of June
2004 to the beginning of July 2004, 10 people had come down with fever,
and, had had symptoms consistent with anthrax infection. As a result,
martial law had been enforced in the county. The milk supply area had been
disinfected, and cattle in the area had been vaccinated.
Confirmation of the source of infection is still pending. During the 1st
half of 2004, 20 people were diagnosed with anthrax in Mongolia, the
majority being infected through domestic animals [animals from household
farms].

[Byline: Wu Pengfei]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[On the webpage of the above article, there were links to 2 earlier
articles: The 1st article mentioned an anthrax infection in a herdsman from
Ulaanbaatar, having been diagnosed on 4 May 2004 after contact with a cow
that died of probable anthrax. 23 800 cattle were vaccinated in the
surrounding region in response to that case
(<http://news.xinhuanet.com/world/2004-05/07/content_1455458.htm>).

The 2nd article referred to a case of anthrax, in a horse, in Kent
Province, with a resultant vaccination of more than 300 domestic animals
(<http://news.xinhuanet.com/world/2004-04/30/content_1449430.htm>). - Mod.MPP]
