[2]
Date: 20 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: UB Post, 29 Jun 2004 [edited]
<http://ubpost.mongolnews.mn/national.php?subaction=showfull&id=1088524741&archive=&cnshow=news&start_from=&ucat=6&>

Ulaanbaatar: anthrax virus reported in the north
-----------------------------------------------
According to the National Center of Infectious Diseases with Natural Foci,
a citizen from the Ondor-Ulaan soum, Arkhangai, has been diagnosed
cutaneous anthrax. It is not clear how the patient was infected, although
none of those in direct contact with the patient have tested positive for
the [bacillus]. For now, the patient remains in isolation in the local
hospital.
3 people in Darkhan-Uul aimag, and 4 people in Selenge aimag [provinces],
are also in isolation, having shown symptoms of being exposed to the
anthrax virus [not a virus but a bacillus].
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Included with the above article from the UB Post was a reader's comments
posted on 8 Jul 2004: "Anthrax is a bacterial disease caused by _Bacillus
anthracis_ (_B. anthracis_). This disease has a world-wide distribution,
and, chiefly affects cattle, sheep, horses, pigs, and, less frequently,
other species of domesticated animals. The disease also occurs in a variety
of wild animals. Human infections with _B. anthracis_ are of animal origin,
and, usually occur through abrasions in the skin or mucous membranes, and,
less commonly, from inhalation. The incidence is relatively high among
those who handle infected carcasses, and animal products, including
bone-meal, feeding stuffs, hides, wool, and hair. The risk is particularly
great for veterinarians, farmers, and personnel working on docks and
factories, handling and processing these infected animal products. The
usual lesion is a malignant pustule that may take some 48 hours to develop,
following an infectious skin abrasion. Infection by inhalation of spores
can occur in certain commercial processes, for example, in wool factories.
Some individuals show remarkable resistance to this route of infection.
When clinical infection does become established, it is acute and severe,
with the development of hemorrhages and edema involving both lungs, and,
the local lymph glands. Septicemia may develop."
Mongolia suffers a steady stream of anthrax outbreaks each year. Proactive
area vaccination should be considered in those parts with repeated
outbreaks. Reactive vaccination of exposed livestock buys only a modest
number of months before new cases appear, as vaccination is not continued.
This scenario has been played out already in Alberta, Saskatchewan and
Manitoba. It is wiser to do as the Cypriots did in their successful
eradication program: define those regions with an ongoing problem,
vaccinate each herd and flock each year, just before the summer "anthrax
season," for at least 5 years, and use repeated annual vaccination just in
those areas/farms where cases continue to appear. Combined with prompt
reporting of all cases, and proper disposal [burning] of carcasses, this
eradication program works. - Mod.MHJ]
